<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Heading 1</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from Women on Boards UK [CEP0003]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women on Boards UK is a UK-wide </span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">organisation for women seeking to leverage their professional skills and experience into board and leadership roles.  Our focus is to encourage, inspire and actively support women - from all sectors - to find their own pathway to the boardroom.</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Our goal i</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s a measurable and sustainable increase in the number of women on boards and in leadership roles across all sectors in the UK.  We provide a complementary service for charities to advertise board vacancies and support our members to apply for trustee roles</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.  Currently we have 4700 members in the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Women on Boards UK:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Supports the requirement for charities reporting under FRS 102 to disclose the total amount of employee benefits received by key management personnel (as per the Charities SORP – Exposure </span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Draft, issued by The Charity Commission for England and Wales and the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator in July 2013), but does not support a statutory benefits cap on employees in the charity sector;</span></li><li style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Supports mandatory disclosure of gender pay gap </span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">information for organisations in all sectors, covering entry level employees through to senior management.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Disclosure of salaries of senior staff</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Under the Charities SORP, charities are already required to disclose in their accounts the number of staff pa</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">id over £60,000, in £10,000 bands.  Women on Boards supports extending this requirement to disclose the total amount of employee benefits received by any individual employee paid over £100,000. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.womenonboards.co.uk/resource-centre/reports/board/index.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">2012 </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Women Count:</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Charity leaders 2012 report provided evidence that – as the sector with the most female CEOs - the charity sector is an important training sector for women, equipping them to move into executive and board ro</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">les on the FTSE and in private companies and the public sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women on Boards does not support a statutory cap on salaries in the charity sector as we believe reducing the pay of CEOs in this sector would further disadvantage already underpaid women wor</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">king in this sector, and would lead to a reduction in the caliber of the women seeking the CEO roles with obvious knock-on implications.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#575656; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Disclosure of gender pay gap for all levels of the organization</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The 2011/2012 annual pay survey of the Association of Chief Executive Officers of Voluntary Organisations reports a pay gap of 16% between male and female chief executives in voluntary bodies with the pay gap rising to almost 30% for some roles.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women o</span><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n Boards believes that requiring organisations in all sectors to analyse and report their gender pay gap publically, is the single most important step that can be taken towards reducing these inequities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#404040; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>